            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this car lease calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator follows the standard lease formula used by banks
                and captive finance companies. It breaks your payment into two
                parts:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Depreciation charge</strong> – what you pay as the car
                  loses value during the lease.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Finance charge</strong> – interest on the money the
                  lender has tied up in the car.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Key definitions</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    <strong>MSRP / Price</strong> = sticker price or negotiated
                    selling price.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Cap cost reduction</strong> = down payment, trade‑in
                    credit, rebates applied to the lease.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Adjusted cap cost</strong> = price + capitalized
                    fees − cap cost reduction.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Residual value</strong> = expected value of the car
                    at lease end.
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>Money factor (MF)</strong> ≈ APR ÷ 2400.</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Formulas</strong></p>
                <p>Adjusted cap cost:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ C_{\text{adj}} = \text{Price} + \text{Cap Fees} - \text{Cap
                  Reduction} \]
                </p>
                <p>Residual (if given as % of MSRP):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ R = \text{MSRP} \times \frac{\text{Residual \%}}{100} \]
                </p>
                <p>Monthly depreciation charge:</p>
                <p>\[ D = \frac{C_{\text{adj}} - R}{N} \]</p>
                <p>Monthly finance charge:</p>
                <p>\[ F = (C_{\text{adj}} + R) \times \text{MF} \]</p>
                <p>Base monthly payment (before tax):</p>
                <p>\[ P_{\text{base}} = D + F \]</p>
                <p>Monthly tax (if tax on payment):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ T_{\text{month}} = P_{\text{base}} \times \frac{\text{Tax
                  \%}}{100} \]
                </p>
                <p>Total monthly payment:</p>
                <p>
                  \[ P_{\text{total}} = P_{\text{base}} + T_{\text{month}} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Understanding each input</h3>
              <h4>Vehicle price (MSRP or negotiated)</h4>
              <p>
                Use the <strong>negotiated selling price</strong> if you have
                it; otherwise use MSRP as an estimate. A lower price directly
                reduces your adjusted cap cost and monthly payment.
              </p>

              <h4>Down payment / cap cost reduction</h4>
              <p>
                This is money you pay upfront to reduce the amount being
                financed. It lowers your monthly payment but barely changes the
                total cost, because you are simply prepaying part of the
                depreciation.
              </p>
              <p>
                For most drivers, it is safer to keep this number low and hold
                onto your cash.
              </p>

              <h4>Lease term</h4>
              <p>
                Common terms are 24, 36, 39 and 48 months. Longer terms lower
                the monthly payment but increase the risk of being out of
                warranty or owing more than the car is worth if you need to exit
                early.
              </p>

              <h4>Residual value</h4>
              <p>
                The residual is set by the leasing bank and is usually
                non‑negotiable. Higher residuals mean you pay for less
                depreciation, so your payment is lower. Luxury brands often have
                high residuals to keep lease payments attractive.
              </p>

              <h4>Money factor and APR</h4>
              <p>
                The money factor is the lease equivalent of an interest rate.
                The relationship is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ \text{APR} \approx \text{Money Factor} \times 2400 \]</p>
                <p>Example: MF = 0.00125 ⇒ APR ≈ 0.00125 × 2400 = 3.0\%</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Use the lower of the dealer quote and any promotional rate you
                qualify for.
              </p>

              <h4>Sales tax</h4>
              <p>
                Tax treatment varies by region. This calculator assumes tax is
                applied to the monthly payment. Some states tax the full selling
                price upfront; in that case, you can approximate by adding that
                tax amount to the <strong>upfront costs</strong> field.
              </p>

              <h4>Fees and upfront costs</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Capitalized fees</strong> (acquisition fee, some
                  dealer fees) are rolled into the lease and increase your
                  payment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Upfront costs</strong> (first payment, DMV, doc fee)
                  are paid at signing and shown separately in the total
                  out‑of‑pocket figure.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Interpreting the results</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Adjusted cap cost</strong> – the amount you are
                  effectively financing.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total depreciation paid</strong> – how much value you
                  are using up during the lease.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total finance charge</strong> – the cost of borrowing,
                  similar to interest on a loan.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total lease payments</strong> – sum of all monthly
                  payments including tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total out‑of‑pocket</strong> – total lease payments
                  plus upfront costs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cost per mile</strong> – helpful for comparing to
                  owning or to other transportation options.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Leasing vs buying: when does leasing make sense?</h2>
              <p>Leasing can be attractive if you:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Prefer a new car every 2–4 years.</li>
                <li>Drive predictable, moderate mileage.</li>
                <li>
                  Want a lower monthly payment compared to a similar loan.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Can deduct lease payments for business use (check with a tax
                  professional).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>Buying may be better if you:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Drive high mileage or plan to keep the car for many years.
                </li>
                <li>Want to build equity and eventually drive payment‑free.</li>
                <li>Prefer to customize the car without lease restrictions.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use this lease calculator together with an
                <a
                  href="https://calcdomain.com/auto-loan"
                  class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                  >auto loan calculator</a
                >
                to compare total costs over the same time period.
              </p>

              <h2>Common car lease questions</h2>

              <h3>What is a good lease deal?</h3>
              <p>
                There is no single magic number, but strong leases usually have:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  A <strong>monthly payment</strong> roughly equal to or less
                  than 1% of MSRP (before tax) for mainstream cars.
                </li>
                <li>
                  A <strong>money factor</strong> close to current new‑car loan
                  rates.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Minimal or no <strong>down payment</strong> beyond standard
                  fees.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>How do excess miles affect my cost?</h3>
              <p>
                If you exceed your mileage allowance, you pay a per‑mile fee
                (often $0.15–$0.30). To estimate the impact:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Estimate your actual annual mileage.</li>
                <li>Subtract the allowance to get extra miles per year.</li>
                <li>
                  Multiply by the excess mileage fee and the number of years.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The <strong>excess mileage fee</strong> input lets you see how
                much extra you might owe at lease end.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I end a lease early?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, but early termination is usually expensive. You may owe the
                remaining payments, an early termination fee, and negative
                equity if the car is worth less than the payoff amount. If you
                think you might need flexibility, consider a shorter term or
                buying instead.
              </p>
